<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Covered compensation is a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">35-year</FONT> average of the maximum earnings recognized in calculating Social Security benefits. For 2016, the covered compensation amount for an individual
attaining age 65 was $75,180, while for an employee age 35 or younger it was $118,500. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Prior to 2001, the Pension Plan operated under a traditional
annuity formula (a normal retirement benefit equal to 1&nbsp;percent of final average pay and 0.65&nbsp;percent of such pay in excess of covered compensation for each of the first 30 years of credited service plus 0.75&nbsp;percent of average pay
for any additional years). As part of the transition to the pension equity formula, as of December&nbsp;31, 2000: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Accrued benefits under the traditional annuity formula were converted to an initial pension equity percentage by calculating the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">lump-sum</FONT> value of the normal retirement annuity
and dividing by the average annual pay at that time. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Anyone who had 5 years of participation and whose age plus vesting service equaled at least 50 years was entitled to additional pension equity credits of 4&nbsp;percent of final average annual pay per year for each year
of employment through 2015. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>ITW Irish Pension Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Irish Pension Plan operates under a traditional annuity formula (a normal retirement benefit equal to 1.5&nbsp;percent of final average pay for each year of credited
service). The final average pay is the highest consecutive pensionable base salary over any three-year period over the last ten complete years of service. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">41 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Nonqualified Pension Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Nonqualified Pension Plan is maintained to make up for benefits that cannot be paid under the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> Pension Plan due
to Internal Revenue Code limitations on the amount of compensation that may be considered and the amount of benefit that may be paid. The Company has not considered awarding additional years of service to executive officers under the plan and,
therefore, does not currently have a policy on such awards. For the most part, the Nonqualified Pension Plan uses the same formulas and other computation elements as the Pension Plan with certain exceptions, including the following: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The Pension Plan uses net compensation after deferrals under the Executive Contributory Retirement Income Plan (the &#147;ECRIP&#148;), and the Nonqualified Pension Plan uses total eligible compensation (generally,
salary and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-equity</FONT> incentive compensation). </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The Nonqualified Pension Plan provides that a participant who leaves the Company, other than upon retirement, may forfeit any plan benefits based on eligible compensation above the IRS maximum amount ($265,000 in 2016)
that may be recognized under a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> plan. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">In addition to the annuity and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">lump-sum</FONT> options available under the Pension Plan, a participant in the Nonqualified Pension Plan may elect to receive fixed monthly installments
over 2 to 20 years. If the executive left employment prior to death, disability or retirement, or if the plan is terminated in conjunction with a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> the
benefit from the Nonqualified Pension Plan would be paid as a lump sum. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Nonqualified Deferred Compensation
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company&#146;s ECRIP offers designated executives an opportunity to defer a portion of their salary and earned
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-equity</FONT> incentive to a deferred compensation account to receive the employer contributions they would otherwise receive if such deferrals had been made under our
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> 401(k) Savings and Investment Plan. Deferred amounts receive a rate of interest based on the monthly Moody&#146;s Long-Term Corporate Bond Yield Average (the &#147;Moody&#146;s Rate&#148;). All
of the NEOs are eligible for the ECRIP. An ECRIP participant can defer from 6&nbsp;percent to 50&nbsp;percent of his or her salary and from 6&nbsp;percent to 85&nbsp;percent of his or her <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-equity</FONT> (annual
and LTI Cash) incentive, with the applicable matching contribution on either component under the Savings and Investment Plan formula (in lieu of any matching contributions under that plan). Deferrals under the ECRIP reduce the compensation that may
be recognized under the Savings and Investment Plan and the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> Pension Plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The ECRIP has a limit on the amount
of interest under the Moody&#146;s Rate that would be recognized (12&nbsp;percent annualized, or 15.6&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible to receive 130&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate), a return of deferral feature whereby an individual could
elect to receive a return of the principal amount deferred after a period of at least five years, and options for payment following death, disability or retirement as a lump sum or in monthly installments over 2 to 20 years. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Retirement under the ECRIP is defined as having attained age 55 with at least 10 years of service, or age 65 with at least 5 years of service. If an ECRIP
participant&#146;s employment ends due to retirement, death, or disability, amounts deferred to the ECRIP prior to January&nbsp;1, 2010 would receive interest crediting of 130&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate. Amounts deferred to the ECRIP
after December&nbsp;31, 2009 are not eligible to receive 130&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate and would receive interest crediting at 100&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate. During 2016, the Moody&#146;s Rate applied to ECRIP accounts ranged
from 3.72&nbsp;percent to 4.57&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible for 100&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate, and 4.84&nbsp;percent to 5.95&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible for 130&nbsp;percent of Moody&#146;s. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">42 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If terminated in conjunction with a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> participants would receive their ECRIP as a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">lump-sum</FONT> payment, as if a retirement event had occurred. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table sets forth ECRIP account information for each NEO during fiscal year 2016. Other than the distributions shown below, there were no withdrawals by, or
distributions to, an NEO under the ECRIP in 2016. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:3%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">*Mr.&nbsp;Nagarajan was not an NEO in 2014 or 2015. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><A NAME="rom291322_26"></A>Potential Payments upon Termination </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #821928">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Payments and benefits received by NEOs upon termination are
governed by the arrangements described below and quantified at the end of this section. We have estimated the amounts involved assuming that the termination became effective as of December&nbsp;30, 2016, the last business day of fiscal year 2016.
The actual amounts to be paid out can only be determined at the time of the NEOs&#146; departure from the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">No payments or benefits are automatically payable
to NEOs upon a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> and if there is a qualifying termination following a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> there are no 280G tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> payments. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Annual Executive Incentive Plan </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
Executive Incentive Plan (&#147;EIP&#148;) provides that if a participant is employed as of the last day of the fiscal year, he or she would receive any amounts earned under the Executive Incentive Plan for that fiscal year. In the event an NEO
becomes permanently disabled or dies, the NEO would be eligible for a possible payout under the Executive Incentive Plan. If termination of employment other than for death, disability, retirement or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> occurs prior to the last day of the fiscal year, a participant forfeits his or her award; however, the Compensation Committee has the discretion to award an amount prorated for the portion
of the fiscal year that the participant was employed. Actual amounts earned based on performance by the NEOs in 2016 are discussed in more detail above in &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis &#151; Components of the 2016 Executive
Compensation Program &#151; Annual Executive Incentive Plan.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>ITW Retirement Accumulation Plan and Nonqualified Pension Plan
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">NEOs who are terminated for any reason receive their benefits under the ITW Retirement Accumulation Plan and Nonqualified Pension Plan as described
in the Pension Benefits table above. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Executive Contributory Retirement Income Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">NEOs who are terminated for any reason receive contributions and accumulated earnings as outlined in the Nonqualified Deferred Compensation section above. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">44 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Long-Term Incentive Plan Awards </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Stock Options and PRSUs: In the event of a termination upon death or disability, all unvested options and PRSUs held by the NEOs would immediately vest. For awards
granted prior to 2014, in the event of a termination upon retirement (defined as age 62 with 10 years of service or age 65 with 5 years of service), unvested options and PRSUs awarded more than one year prior to retirement would immediately vest,
and unvested options and PRSUs awarded within one year prior to retirement would become 25&nbsp;percent vested. Beginning with awards made in 2014, retirement is defined as a combined age and service of 70, subject to a minimum age of 55 and a
minimum service of 5 years, and unvested options will continue to vest according to the original vesting schedule instead of immediately vesting in the event of a recipient&#146;s retirement more than one year after the grant date of the award.
Messrs.&nbsp;Santi and Parry met the retirement criteria for the 2014, 2015 and 2016 awards as of December&nbsp;31, 2016. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In the event of a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> options and PRSUs that are continued or replaced would only vest upon a termination of employment after the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> Unvested options and PRSUs that are not replaced would fully vest. In the case of PRSUs, all such vesting events are subject to the achievement of performance goals. For all NEOs, in the
event of a termination other than upon retirement, death, disability or a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> any unvested options and PRSUs held on such date by the NEOs would be
forfeited. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">LTI Cash: In the event of a termination upon death or disability, the LTI Cash award would vest based on actual performance level achieved and be paid
after the end of the performance period. In the event of a termination upon retirement (defined as termination after age 62 with 10 years of service or age 65 with 5 years of service for awards prior to 2014; beginning in 2014, defined as a combined
age and service of 70, subject to a minimum age of 55 and a minimum service of 5 years), the LTI Cash award would vest <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> and be paid after the end of the performance period. In the event of a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> an LTI Cash award that is not replaced will vest <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> at the greater of target or actual achievement level. In
the event of an actual or constructive termination following a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> an LTI Cash award that has been replaced would vest
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> and be paid at the target level (or actual achievement level if greater). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance Policy </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Effective January&nbsp;1, 2011, the
Company adopted the 2011 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance Compensation Policy, which provides that, upon an actual or constructive termination following a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> of the Company, the NEOs and other elected officers would be entitled to receive: (i)&nbsp;two times annual cash compensation (base salary plus average
annual incentive pay over the prior three years); (ii)&nbsp;a prorated amount of that year&#146;s annual incentive bonus at the target level (or actual achievement level if greater); and (iii)&nbsp;a prorated amount of the value of any LTI Cash
awards at the target level (or actual achievement level if greater). We do not gross up any of the compensation paid in the event of termination due to a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">45 </P>

Stock&nbsp;Options</P></TD>

<TD VALIGN="middle" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">If retirement is 1 year or more after award: Pre-2014 awards &#150; vests 100&nbsp;percent; Post-2013 awards &#150;&nbsp;Continue vesting (3); if less than 1&nbsp;year, 25&nbsp;percent
vests and 75&nbsp;percent is forfeited</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" NOWRAP ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">N/A</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" NOWRAP ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">100&nbsp;percent<BR>vesting</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt">Subject to replacement and double trigger (5); otherwise, 100&nbsp;percent vesting</TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#d8d8d8" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Payment of
Long-Term Cash (LTI Cash)(2)(3)</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pro-rata</FONT> vesting (4)</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" NOWRAP ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">N/A</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" NOWRAP ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">100 percent<BR>vesting&nbsp;(4)</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt">Subject to replacement and double trigger (5); otherwise, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> amount based on termination
date (6)</TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Retirement for these awards is defined as termination after age 55 and 10 years of service. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">All vesting for these awards is subject to achievement of performance goals, except for termination upon death or disability. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Retirement for awards granted through 2013 is defined as termination after age 62 with 10 years of service or age 65 with 5 years of service. For awards granted in 2014 and later, retirement is defined as a combination
of age and service of 70 with a minimum age of 55 and minimum service of 5 years. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">46 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Vesting is limited to the extent that the performance level for the award is achieved. If the minimum performance level is not achieved, the award is forfeited. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(5)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Awards that are replaced after a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> do not receive accelerated vesting. Double-trigger vesting occurs for awards that are
continued or replaced if actual or constructive termination occurs within two years of a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> of the Company. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(6)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pro-rata</FONT> vesting is at the greater of target or actual achievement level. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#821928"><B><A NAME="rom291322_28"></A>Termination and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Payments and Benefits </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #821928">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the value of payments and benefits
that the NEOs would receive pursuant to the 2011 Long-Term Incentive Plan, the 2015 Long-Term Incentive Plan and the 2011 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-In-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance Compensation Policy
upon retirement, involuntary termination without cause, death, disability or a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> assuming that termination occurred as of the last business day of
fiscal 2016. It also shows the Company&#146;s severance benefits that would be payable to the NEOs and that are available to employees generally. For purposes of this table, LTI Cash payment is assumed at target level. The value of unvested stock
options and PRSUs, if accelerated upon a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> or termination, is&nbsp;determined using the excess, if any, of $122.46 (the closing price of ITW common stock
on December&nbsp;30, 2016) over the option exercise price. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Santi and Mr.&nbsp;Parry met the retirement criteria for various grants under the Long-Term
Incentive Plan during 2016. Since Mr.&nbsp;Santi does not meet the retirement criteria for his 2013 stock options, the unvested options would be forfeited. Mr.&nbsp;Parry&#146;s unvested 2013 stock options would accelerate. The 2014 and 2015 PRSUs,
LTI Cash awards and stock options continue vesting. In addition, 75&nbsp;percent of the 2016 PRSU and stock option awards would be forfeited since the assumed retirement occurs within the award year. The LTI Cash award would be <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rated</FONT> based on the retirement date. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Voluntary termination without good reason is not shown in the table because such a
termination would not trigger the payment of severance benefits or annual long-term incentives. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

confidential information about, the Company, or if the Compensation Committee determines that the holder engaged in gross misconduct or conduct that is against the business interests of the Company. Awards granted after January&nbsp;1, 2011 are also
subject to forfeiture, in whole or in part, in order to comply with applicable law, regulation, stock exchange, accounting rule, or our clawback policy. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#821928"><B><A NAME="rom291322_29"></A>Equity Compensation Plan Information </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #821928">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><A NAME="rom291322_30"></A>Compensation Committee Report </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #821928">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors hereby
furnishes the following report to the stockholders of the Company in accordance with rules adopted by the Securities and Exchange Commission. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and
discussed with management the Compensation Discussion and Analysis contained in this proxy statement. Based on our review and discussions, we have recommended to the Board of Directors that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in
this proxy statement and the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">This report is submitted on behalf of the members of the Compensation Committee: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">James A. Skinner, Chairman </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Susan Crown </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">James W. Griffith </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Richard H. Lenny </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Robert S. Morrison </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:69%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Anr&eacute; D. Williams </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">49 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><A NAME="rom291322_31"></A>Certain Relationships and Related Party Transactions
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We review related-party transactions in accordance with our Statement of Principles of Conduct, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and
Corporate Governance Guidelines, rather than a separate written policy. A related-party transaction is a transaction involving the Company and any of the following persons: a director, director nominee or executive officer of the Company; a holder
of more than 5% of ITW common stock; or an immediate family member or person sharing the household of any of these persons. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Statement of Principles of Conduct
states that our directors, officers and employees must avoid engaging in any activity, such as related-party transactions, that might create a conflict of interest or a perception of a conflict of interest. These individuals are required to raise
for consideration any proposed or actual transaction that they believe may create a conflict of interest. Our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide that no related-party transaction is void or voidable solely because a director has
an interest if (1)&nbsp;the material facts are disclosed to or known by the Board of Directors and the transaction is approved by the disinterested directors or an appropriate Board committee comprised of disinterested directors, (2)&nbsp;the
material facts are disclosed to or known by the stockholders and the transaction is approved by the stockholders, or (3)&nbsp;the transaction is fair to the Company as of the time it is approved. Our Corporate Governance Guidelines provide that the
Board will apply established Categorical Standards for Director Independence in making its independence determinations. Under the standards, certain relationships between the Company and a director would preclude a director from being considered
independent. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">On an annual basis, each director and executive officer completes a Directors&#146; and Officers&#146; Questionnaire, which requires disclosure of any
transactions with the Company in which he or she, or any member of his or her immediate family, has a direct or indirect material interest. The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee reviews these questionnaires and discusses any
related-party transaction disclosed therein. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In addition, under its charter, the Audit Committee is responsible for reviewing, approving, ratifying or disapproving
all proposed related-party transactions that, if entered into, would be required to be disclosed under the rules and regulations of the SEC. In reviewing related-party transactions, the Audit Committee considers the factors set forth in our
Statement of Principles of Conduct, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and Corporate Governance Guidelines, as well as other factors, including the Company&#146;s rationale for entering into the transaction, alternatives to the
transaction, whether the transaction is on terms at least as fair to the Company as would be the case were the transaction entered into with a third party, and the potential for an actual or apparent conflict of interest. No member of the Audit
Committee having an interest in a related-party transaction may participate in any decision regarding that transaction. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The son of David C. Parry, one of ITW&#146;s
Vice Chairmen in 2016, is employed by the Company and earned fiscal year 2016 compensation in excess of $120,000. His compensation was comparable to other employees in a similar job position. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We maintain a commercial banking relationship with The Northern Trust Company and its wholly owned subsidiaries. The Northern Trust Company is a wholly owned subsidiary
of Northern Trust Corporation and beneficially owns approximately 11.8% of our common stock. Ms.&nbsp;Susan Crown and Messrs. Jay L. Henderson and David&nbsp;B. Smith, Jr., directors of the Company, are also directors of Northern Trust Corporation
and The Northern Trust Company. In 2016, The Northern Trust Company provided the following services to the Company: credit services, treasury and investment management services, trade services, credit enhancement or payment guaranty, acting as agent
or fiduciary, consulting services, risk management services, securities lending services and broker dealer services. In addition, The Northern Trust Company serves as the trustee under the Company&#146;s principal U.S. pension plans. The banking and
trustee relationships with The Northern Trust Company are conducted in the ordinary course of business on an <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">arm&#146;s-length</FONT> basis. Banking, investment management, trustee and other administrative fees paid
to The Northern Trust Company or affiliates by the Company were approximately $2.6&nbsp;million in 2016. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">50 </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><A NAME="rom291322_32"></A>Audit Committee Report </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee of the Board of Directors is composed of seven independent directors, as defined in the listing standards of the New York Stock Exchange, and the
Board of Directors has determined that all Audit Committee members are &#147;financially literate.&#148; In addition, the Board of Directors has determined that Messrs.&nbsp;Brutto and Henderson meet the Securities and Exchange Commission criteria
of &#147;audit committee financial expert.&#148; The Audit Committee operates under a written charter adopted by the Board of Directors, which was most recently reviewed by the Audit Committee in February 2017. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is responsible for providing oversight to the Company&#146;s financial reporting process through periodic meetings with ITW&#146;s independent
registered public accountants, internal auditors and management in order to review accounting, auditing, internal control and financial reporting matters. The Audit Committee is also responsible for assisting the Board in overseeing: (a)&nbsp;the
integrity of the Company&#146;s financial statements; (b)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s compliance with legal and regulatory requirements; (c)&nbsp;the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s qualifications, independence and performance;
(d)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s overall risk policies and practices; and (e)&nbsp;the performance of the Company&#146;s internal audit function. Company management is responsible for the preparation and integrity of the financial reporting information
and related systems of internal controls. The Audit Committee, in carrying out its role, relies on Company senior management, including senior financial management, and ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following is the report of the Audit Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed
with senior management the audited financial statements of the Company. Management has confirmed to the Audit Committee that the financial statements have been prepared in conformity with generally accepted accounting principles. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed with senior management their assertion and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s internal controls. Management has confirmed to the Audit
Committee that internal controls over financial reporting have been appropriately designed and are operating effectively to prevent or detect any material financial statement misstatements. We have also reviewed and discussed with
Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP, ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm, its audit and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s internal controls. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We
have reviewed and discussed with Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP the matters required to be discussed by PCAOB Auditing Standard No.&nbsp;1301 (Communications with Audit Committees) under which Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP must provide us with
additional information regarding the scope and results of its audit of the Company&#146;s financial statements. This information includes: (1)&nbsp;Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP&#146;s responsibility under generally accepted auditing standards;
(2)&nbsp;significant accounting policies; (3)&nbsp;management judgments and estimates; (4)&nbsp;any significant audit adjustments or internal control matters; (5)&nbsp;any disagreements with management; and (6)&nbsp;any difficulties encountered in
performing the audit. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have received from Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP a letter providing the disclosures required by applicable requirements of the Public
Company Accounting Oversight Board regarding the independent accountant&#146;s communications with the Audit Committee concerning independence with respect to any relationships between Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP and the Company that in its
professional judgment may reasonably be thought to bear on independence. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP has discussed its independence with us, and it has confirmed in the letter that, in its professional judgment, it is in a position to serve the
Company as its Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee also discussed with the Company&#146;s internal auditors and independent
registered public accounting firm the overall scope and plans for their respective audits. The Audit Committee meets periodically with the internal auditors and independent registered public accounting firm, with
</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">51 </P>

and without management present, to discuss the results of their examinations, their evaluations of the Company&#146;s internal controls, and the overall quality of the Company&#146;s financial
reporting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Based on the reviews and discussions described above, we recommended to the Board of Directors, and the Board approved, the inclusion of the audited
financial statements in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, for filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. </P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><A NAME="rom291322_33"></A>Proposal 2 - Ratification of the Appointment of
Independent </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B>Registered Public Accounting Firm </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is directly responsible for the appointment, compensation, retention and oversight of the independent registered public accounting firm retained to
audit ITW&#146;s financial statements. The Audit Committee is also directly involved in the selection of the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s new lead engagement partner in conjunction with the mandatory rotation of the lead
engagement partner. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee has engaged Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP (&#147;Deloitte&#148;) to serve as ITW&#146;s independent registered public
accounting firm for the fiscal year ending December&nbsp;31, 2017. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP has been employed to perform this function for the Company since 2002. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Audit Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Deloitte, the member firms of
Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, and their respective affiliates (collectively, the &#147;Deloitte Entities&#148;) will bill us approximately $9,646,000 for professional services in connection with the 2016 audit, as compared with $10,019,000 for the 2015
audit of the annual financial statements and internal controls. These fees relate to: (i)&nbsp;the audit of the annual financial statements included in our Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K;</FONT> (ii)&nbsp;the review of
the quarterly financial statements included in our Quarterly Reports on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-Q;</FONT> (iii)&nbsp;the internal controls audit; and (iv)&nbsp;statutory audits. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Audit-Related Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">During 2016 and 2015,
the Deloitte Entities billed us approximately $155,000 and $268,000, respectively, for audit-related services. These fees relate to work performed with respect to technical accounting assistance and comfort letters related to debt issuances. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Tax Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">These fees include work
performed by the Deloitte Entities for 2016 and 2015 with respect to tax compliance services such as assistance in preparing various types of tax returns globally ($1,215,000 and $1,442,000, respectively) and tax planning services, often related to
our restructurings and new tax rules ($517,000 and $1,562,000, respectively). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>All Other Fees </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">There were no fees for other services rendered by the Deloitte Entities for 2016 and 2015. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Audit Committee <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pre-Approval</FONT> Policies </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee has adopted policies and procedures for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> of all audit and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related work to be performed by ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. As a part of those procedures, the Audit Committee performs a qualitative analysis of all <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> work to be performed by our independent registered public accounting firm. Each year, the Audit Committee receives a detailed list of the types of audit-related and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related services to be performed, along with estimated fee amounts. The Audit Committee then reviews and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</FONT> audit work and certain categories of tax
and other <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services that may be performed. In conducting its analysis, the Audit Committee carefully contemplates the nature of the services to be provided and considers whether such services:
(i)&nbsp;are prohibited under applicable rules; (ii)&nbsp;would result in our accountants auditing their own work; (iii)&nbsp;would result in our accountants performing management functions; (iv)&nbsp;would place our accountants in a position of
acting as an advocate for the Company; or (v)&nbsp;would present a real risk of a conflict of interest or otherwise impair our accountants&#146; independence. The Audit Committee also annually <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</FONT> the
budget for annual GAAP, statutory and benefit </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">53 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
plan audits. Company management provides quarterly updates to the Audit Committee regarding <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">year-to-date</FONT></FONT>
expenditures versus budget for audit and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services. The Audit Committee also considers whether specific projects or expenditures could potentially affect the independence of ITW&#146;s independent
registered public accounting firm. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee annually reviews Deloitte&#146;s independence and performance in determining whether to retain Deloitte or
engage another firm as our independent registered public accounting firm. In the course of these reviews, the Audit Committee considers, among other things: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:7%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;Deloitte&#146;s historical and recent performance on the ITW audit; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:7%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;External data relating to audit quality and performance, including recent Public Company
Accounting Oversight Board (&#147;PCAOB&#148;) reports on Deloitte and its peer firms; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:7%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;Deloitte&#146;s independence; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:7%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;The appropriateness of Deloitte&#146;s fees, on both an absolute basis and as compared to
its peer firms; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:7%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;Deloitte&#146;s tenure as our independent auditor and its familiarity
with our global operations and businesses, accounting policies and practices and internal control over financial reporting; and </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:7%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;Deloitte&#146;s capability and expertise in handling the breadth and complexity of our global operations. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Based on this evaluation, the Audit Committee believes that Deloitte is independent and that it is in the best interests of the Company and our stockholders to retain
Deloitte to serve as our independent registered public accounting firm for 2017. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Although we are not required to do so, we believe that it is appropriate for us to
request stockholder ratification of the appointment of Deloitte as our independent registered public accounting firm. If stockholders do not ratify the appointment, the Audit Committee will investigate the reasons for the stockholders&#146;
rejection and reconsider the appointment. Representatives of Deloitte will be present at our Annual Meeting and will have the opportunity to make a statement and respond to questions. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>The Board of Directors recommends a vote &#147;FOR&#148; ratification of the appointment of </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP </B></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">54 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><A NAME="rom291322_34"></A>Proposal 3 - Advisory Vote on Executive Compensation
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In accordance with the recommendation by the Board and the preference expressed by our stockholders at the 2011 Annual Meeting, the Company has an
advisory vote on executive compensation annually. The Company is seeking your advisory vote on our executive compensation, as disclosed in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; section, the compensation tables and any related material
disclosed in this proxy statement pursuant to the SEC&#146;s compensation disclosure rules. The Compensation Committee will review the voting results and take them into consideration when making future decisions regarding executive compensation, but
because your vote is advisory, it will not be binding on the Compensation Committee, the Board or the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We believe that our executive compensation program is
competitive and strongly aligned with our Enterprise Strategy performance goals and the long-term interests of our stockholders. Our compensation program and structure are more fully described in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148;
and &#147;NEO Compensation&#148; sections of this proxy statement. We encourage you to closely review this information before voting on the compensation we paid to our NEOs in 2016. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We ask our stockholders to approve, on an advisory basis, the compensation of our NEOs by voting &#147;FOR&#148; the following resolution: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:13%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Resolved, </B>that the compensation of the named executive officers of Illinois Tool Works Inc. (the &#147;Company&#148;) as disclosed pursuant to
the compensation disclosure rules of the Securities and Exchange Commission under &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis,&#148; in the Summary Compensation Table, the related compensation tables and the related narrative disclosures in the
Company&#146;s proxy statement for its 2017 Annual Meeting, is hereby approved. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>The Board of Directors recommends a vote &#147;FOR&#148; the
approval of the compensation of </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>the Company&#146;s named executive officers </B></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">55 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><A NAME="rom291322_35"></A>Proposal 4 - Advisory Vote on the Frequency of the
Advisory Vote on Executive Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We are providing shareholders with the opportunity to cast an advisory vote regarding the frequency of advisory
votes on executive compensation, commonly known as <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;say-on-pay&#148;</FONT></FONT> votes. Shareholders may vote on whether the advisory vote on executive compensation should
occur every one, two or three years. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We are required to hold an advisory vote regarding the frequency of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;say-on-pay&#148;</FONT></FONT> votes every six years. The Company&#146;s stockholders were provided with the opportunity to vote on the frequency of
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;say-on-pay&#148;</FONT></FONT> votes in 2011. The stockholders voted in favor of holding
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;say-on-pay&#148;</FONT></FONT> votes annually and the Board adopted this standard. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">After
consideration of each alternative, the Board recommends that the advisory vote on executive compensation continue to be submitted to the stockholders every year. While the Company utilizes three-year performance cycles in its long-term compensation
grants, compensation decisions regarding salary, incentive bonus, stock options and awards of long-term grants are made annually, and an annual vote provides feedback for our Compensation Committee that can be taken into account each year when
making compensation decisions and setting our compensation philosophy, policies and practices. An annual advisory vote is also consistent with our practice of open dialogue with our stockholders. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Your vote on frequency is advisory and will not be binding on the Board or the Company. Although <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-binding,</FONT> the Board and the
Compensation Committee value the views of the Company&#146;s stockholders and will carefully consider the outcome of the frequency vote. Notwithstanding the Board&#146;s recommendation and the outcome of the stockholder vote, the Board may in the
future decide to conduct advisory votes on a more or less frequent basis and may vary its practice based on factors such as discussions with stockholders and the adoption of material changes to compensation programs. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>The Board of Directors recommends a vote for a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">ONE-YEAR</FONT> frequency of the advisory vote on executive
compensation </B></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">56 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><A NAME="rom291322_36"></A>Proposal 5 - To Vote on a Stockholder Proposal to Grant
Stockholders the Right to Act by Written Consent </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has been notified that John Chevedden, whose address is 2215 Nelson Avenue, No.&nbsp;205,
Redondo Beach, California 90278, intends to present the following proposal (the &#147;Stockholder Proposal&#148;) for consideration at the 2017 Annual Meeting. Mr.&nbsp;Chevedden has submitted documentation indicating that he is the beneficial owner
of no less than 100 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You should read carefully the description of the proposal. The Board of Directors recommends that you
vote &#147;AGAINST&#148; the Stockholder Proposal. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Stockholder Proposal and Supporting Statement: </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Resolved, Shareholders request that our board of directors undertake such steps as may be necessary to permit written consent by shareholders entitled
to cast the minimum number of votes that would be necessary to authorize the action at a meeting at which all shareholders entitled to vote thereon were present and voting. This written consent is to be consistent with applicable law and consistent
with giving shareholders the fullest power to act by written consent consistent with applicable law. This includes shareholder ability to initiate any topic for written consent consistent with applicable law. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">This proposal topic won majority shareholder support at 13 major companies in a single year. This included 67%-support at both Allstate and Sprint.
Hundreds of major companies enable shareholder action by written consent. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Taking action by written consent in lieu of a meeting is a means
shareholders can use to raise important matters outside the normal annual meeting cycle. A shareholder right to act by written consent and to call special meeting are 2 complimentary ways to bring an important matter to the attention of both
management and shareholders outside the annual meeting cycle. Taking action by written consent saves the expense of holding a special shareholder meeting. Also our company requires 20% of shareholders to aggregate their shares to call a special
meeting &#150; a much higher hill to climb than the 10% of shareholders permitted by Delaware law. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Please vote to enhance shareholder value: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:11%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Right to Act by Written Consent- Proposal 5 </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Board of Directors Statement in Opposition </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Our Board recommends a vote AGAINST this proposal. </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Board has carefully
considered the Stockholder Proposal and unanimously recommends a vote AGAINST the proposal. The Board believes that stockholder action by written consent is not necessary in light of stockholders&#146; existing ability to call a special meeting. The
Board amended the Company&#146;s Certificate of Incorporation in May 2016 following stockholder approval of a Company proposal to allow stockholders holding 20% of the Company&#146;s voting power to call a special meeting, with no material
restrictions on subject matter. The 20% threshold was requested in a stockholder proposal included in the Company&#146;s proxy statement in 2015. The Board explained in the 2016 proxy statement and continues to believe that an ownership threshold of
20% to call a special meeting achieves a reasonable balance between enhancing stockholder rights and adequately protecting the long-term interests of the Company and its stockholders. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">57 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board believes that a special meeting is a more appropriate method than action by written consent for stockholders to
take action between regular annual meetings, as a special meeting ensures that all stockholders receive notice, adequate time to review proposals and a forum for expressing their views. By contrast, stockholder action by written consent may not
result in all stockholders receiving notice of a proposed action and does not permit a variety of views on a proposal to be exchanged. Action by written consent can also create confusion and disruption, as stockholder groups may solicit multiple
written consents simultaneously, some of which may be duplicative or contradictory. The Board believes that matters of sufficient importance to warrant action between annual stockholder meetings should not be decided without notification to all
stockholders and an opportunity for all stockholders to be heard and to vote at a meeting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company is committed to sound corporate governance and has taken a
number of steps to enhance stockholder rights. In addition to amending the Certificate of Incorporation to allow stockholders to call special meetings, the Company amended its <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> in December of 2015 to
implement proxy access. The Company has also eliminated supermajority provisions in its <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and has an annually elected board, a majority vote standard, a director resignation policy, an anti-hedging and
anti-pledging policy, a compensation recovery (clawback) policy, and no poison pill. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company also regularly engages with its stockholders regarding a variety of
topics, including corporate governance. We invited holders of approximately 51% of our shares, represented by 25 investors, to engage with us regarding this proposal, among other topics. A majority of these investors, holding approximately 29% of
our shares, informed us that they do not support the granting of written consent rights to stockholders, particularly when there is a right to call special meetings, which our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Given the actions that the Company has taken to enhance stockholder rights and its commitment to strong corporate governance, and the existing right of stockholders to
call special meetings, the Board believes that adoption of this proposal would not advance the Company&#146;s or stockholders&#146; interests. For the reasons stated above, the Board of Directors unanimously recommends a vote AGAINST this proposal.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>For the foregoing reasons, the Board of Directors believes that this proposal is not in </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>the best interests of the Company or its stockholders and unanimously recommends </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>that you vote &#147;AGAINST&#148; this proposal </B></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">58 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Who may vote? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Stockholders at the close of business on March&nbsp;7, 2017, the record date, may vote. On that date, there were 345,668,225 shares of ITW common stock outstanding. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>How many votes do I have? </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Each share of
ITW common stock that you own entitles you to one vote. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>How do I vote? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You may vote your shares in one of the following four ways: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Attend our Annual Meeting, where ballots will be provided.</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If you vote by telephone or Internet, you should have your proxy card or Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials, or <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">E-Proxy</FONT> Notice, in hand when you call or go to the proxy vote website. If you hold your shares through a bank or broker that does not offer telephone or Internet voting, please complete and return your proxy card by
mail. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>When must I submit my vote by Internet or by phone? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If you vote by Internet or by phone, you must transmit your vote by 10:59 p.m., Central Time, on May&nbsp;4, 2017. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>If I hold shares through an ITW Savings and Investment 401(k) Plan, when must I submit my vote? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Shares held through an ITW 401(k) plan must be voted by 10:59 p.m., Central Time, on May&nbsp;2, 2017 in order to be tabulated in time for the meeting. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">59 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>How does discretionary voting authority apply? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Stockholders of Record.</I> If you are a stockholder of record and you vote by proxy, the individuals named on the proxy card (your proxies) will vote your shares in
the manner you indicate. If your proxy card does not indicate how you want to vote, your proxy will be voted as follows: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#147;FOR&#148; the election of each
director nominee; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#147;FOR&#148; the ratification of the appointment of Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP as our independent registered public accounting firm for
2017; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#147;FOR&#148; the approval of ITW&#146;s executive compensation; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;ONE-YEAR&#148;</FONT> frequency of the advisory vote on executive compensation; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#147;AGAINST&#148; the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-binding</FONT> stockholder proposal to permit stockholders to act by written consent; and </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#147;FOR&#148; or &#147;AGAINST&#148; any
other properly raised matter at the discretion of Susan Crown, James A. Skinner and Pamela B. Strobel, or any one of them. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Beneficial Owners.</I> If your shares
are held in a brokerage account or by a nominee and you do not provide your broker or nominee with voting instructions, the broker or nominee may represent your shares at the meeting for purposes of obtaining a quorum, but it may not exercise
discretion to vote your shares at the meeting unless the proposal is considered a routine matter. The only matter being proposed for stockholder vote at the 2017 Annual Meeting that is considered a routine matter is the proposal to ratify the
appointment of Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP as our independent registered public accounting firm for 2017. As a result, in the absence of voting instructions from you, your broker or nominee will not have discretion to vote on any other matter to
be voted on at the Annual Meeting. If you are a beneficial owner, it is important that you provide instructions to your bank, broker or other holder of record so that your vote is counted. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>May I revoke my proxy? </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You may revoke
your proxy at any time before it is voted at our Annual Meeting in one of four ways: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Notify our Secretary in writing before our Annual
Meeting that you wish to revoke your proxy; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Submit another proxy with a later date; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Vote by telephone or Internet after you have given your proxy; or </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Vote in person at our Annual Meeting. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>Why didn&#146;t I receive a paper copy of the proxy statement and annual report? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Unless our stockholders have requested paper copies, we are furnishing proxy materials through the Internet. If you received a Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy
Materials <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(E-Proxy</FONT> Notice) by mail or electronically, you will not receive a printed copy of the proxy materials unless you specifically request one. Instead, the
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">E-Proxy</FONT> Notice provides instructions on how you may access and review our proxy materials online. The <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">E-Proxy</FONT> Notice also instructs you on how you may submit your proxy
via the Internet. If you received the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">E-Proxy</FONT> Notice and would still like to receive a printed copy of our proxy materials without charge, you should follow the instructions for requesting such materials
included in the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">E-Proxy</FONT> Notice. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#821928"><B><I>I have received paper copies&#151;how do I receive future proxy
materials electronically? </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To sign up to receive stockholder communications electronically, follow the instructions on your proxy card or <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">E-Proxy</FONT> Notice under &#147;Vote by Internet.&#148; You will need the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> number that is printed in the </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">60 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
